any
faults
detrimental
to
the
interests
of
the
house,
I
shall
dismiss
you
as
I
would
any
other
clerk.
Ninety
pounds
a
year
are
good
wages,
and
I
expect
to
have
the
full
value
of
my
money
out
of
you;
remember,
too,
that
things
are
on
a
practical
footing
in
my
establishment
business
like
habits,
feelings,
and
ideas,
suit
me
best.
Do
you
understand?"
"Partly,"
I
replied.
"I
suppose
you
mean
that
I
am
to
do
my
work
for
my
wages;
not
to
expect
